# Java Quality

## Style

- Match existing code: 4-space indent, `var` for obvious locals, records for immutable data
- Prefer package-private types unless part of a layer's **public API** (SDK, operator entrypoints)
- One public top-level type per file; name matches the file

## Immutability

Domain and API types are immutable. Only infrastructure adapters hold mutable state (clients, caches).

```java
// ✅ GOOD — shared across all layers
public record Query(SourcePipeline sourcePipeline, List<String> sinkTopics) {}

// ❌ BAD — mutable domain object
public class Query { private List<String> sinks; public void addSink(String s) { ... } }
```

## Dependencies

- `parser.model` — JDK only; no Kafka, ANTLR, Jackson, SLF4J, or K8s
- Code layer — no Kafka runtime dependencies
- Application layer — Kafka at the boundary; do not expose Kafka types in public API
- Operator layer — K8s client at the boundary; reconcile logic works on domain types
- Constructor injection; no static mutable state
- SLF4J with `{}` placeholders where logging is used

## Error handling

- Fail fast with clear messages; do not swallow exceptions
- Domain validation errors are distinct from infrastructure failures
- Use `Objects.requireNonNull` at layer boundaries

## Public API (SDK / operator)

- Minimal surface; expose `StreamModel` and fluent builders, not internal parsers or K8s helpers
- Stable method names aligned with Stream Language vocabulary (`from`, `filter`, `to`, not Kafka jargon)
